PB  - INFORMS
N2  - How Near-Miss Events Amplify or Attenuate Risky Decision Making (p. 1596) Catherine H. Tinsley, Robin L. Dillon, Matthew A. Cronin When Hurricane Katrina devastated the Gulf Coast in 2005, the public and media alike wondered why so many people failed to evacuate and why the government and first-responder organizations were not prepared. These questions tend to arise in the aftermath of natural and man-made disasters, and the answers can often be found in people's previous experiences. In the lead-up to Katrina, Governor Haley Barbour of Mississippi warned of ?hurricane fatigue??the possibility that his constituents would not evacuate because they had successfully weathered earlier storms. The authors study the effect of prior ?near-miss? experiences, which they define as events that have some nontrivial expectation of ending in disaster but, by chance, do not. The authors demonstrate that when near misses are interpreted as disasters that did not occur, people illegitimately underestimate the danger of subsequent hazardous situations and make riskier decisions such as not evacuating. On the other hand, recognizing and interpreting near misses as disasters that almost happened will counter the basic ?near-miss? effect and encourage more mitigation. The insight for management: We might learn from our experiences, but we are often misled by near-miss experiences. The Relational Advantages of Intermediation (p. 1614) Elena Belavina, Karan Girotra There has been phenomenal growth of supply chain intermediaries that source products or services on behalf of other firms. These often completely take over the sourcing function: They select, verify, and approve suppliers; they allocate business between different suppliers; and they manage the relationship with each supplier, including provision of incentives for investments, performance, and compliance. The authors provide a novel explanation for the use of supply chain intermediaries. They find that, even in the absence of the well-known transactional and informational advantages of mediation, intermediaries improve supply chain performance. In particular, intermediaries facilitate responsive adaptation of the buyers' supplier base to their changing needs while simultaneously ensuring that suppliers behave as if they had long-term sourcing commitments from buying firms. In the face of changing buyer needs, an intermediary that sources on behalf of multiple buyers can responsively change the composition of future business committed to a supplier such that a sufficient level of business comes from the buyer(s) that most prefer this supplier. On the other hand, direct buyers that source only for themselves must provide all their committed business to a supplier from their own sourcing needs, even if they no longer prefer this supplier. The insight for management: Intermediaries have continued to flourish despite reductions in information asymmetries in the marketplace. Firm Survival and Industry Evolution in Vertically Related Populations (p. 1632) John M. de Figueiredo, Brian S. Silverman How do the density and governance of vertically related populations affect the life chances of organizations? The authors present a theory of how (1) specialized upstream industries affect downstream survival rates, (2) the prevalence of different governance forms among upstream and downstream organizations moderates this relationship, and (3) different forms of governance exert differential competitive pressures on focal organizations. The authors conduct an empirical analysis of the downstream laser printer industry and upstream laser engine industry, finding support for their hypotheses. The insight for management: Density of suppliers in upstream industries affects the survival rates of downstream firms. Link to Success: How Blogs Build an Audience by Promoting Rivals (p. 1651) Dina Mayzlin, Hema Yoganarasimhan Why would competing bloggers link to one another? The authors explain why a rational blogger may choose to link to another blog. Bloggers might differ along two dimensions, such as (1) the ability to post news-breaking content and (2) the ability to find news in other blogs. By linking, a blog signals to the reader that it will be able to direct her to news in other blogs in the future. The downside of a link is that it is a positive signal of the rival's news-breaking ability. One implication of the linking mechanism is that blogs that are high on the news-breaking ability are more likely to gain readers. The insight for management: Despite the fact that bloggers link for purely selfish reasons, the effect of this activity is that readers' learning is enhanced. Comparing Business and Household Sector Innovation in Consumer Products: Findings from a Representative Study in the United Kingdom (p. 1669) Eric von Hippel, Jeroen P. J. de Jong, Stephen Flowers How do consumers and businesses contribute to new product innovation? Based on a sample of 1,173 UK consumers age 18 and older, the authors estimate this type of household sector innovation to be quite large: 6.1% of UK consumers have engaged in consumer product innovation during the prior three years. They also find that, in aggregate, consumers' annual product development expenditures are more than 1.4 times larger than the annual consumer product R they have real impact on pricing and production plans over time. Robust Portfolio Choice with Learning in the Framework of Regret: Single-Period Case (p. 1732) Andrew E. B. Lim, J. George Shanthikumar, Gah-Yi Vahn Do your investment returns keep up with the Joneses? Regardless of portfolio performance, the authors suggest that portfolio value is often measured relative to the performance of someone else. ?Relative regret? evaluates a portfolio by comparing its return to a family of benchmarks, where the benchmarks are the returns of fictitious investors who invest optimally given knowledge of the model parameters. The optimal relative regret portfolio is the one that performs well in relation to all of the benchmarks. The authors' results show that regret is a natural means by which robust decision making and learning can be combined. The insight for management: Portfolio performance is gauged in a relative manner; investing behavior changes based on how alternative portfolios are performing. Intermediated Blind Portfolio Auctions (p. 1747) Michael Padilla, Benjamin Van Roy As much as 12% of the daily volume on the New York Stock Exchange, and similar volumes on other major world exchanges, involves sales by institutional investors to brokers through blind portfolio auctions. Blind portfolio auctions typically take the form of a first-price sealed-bid auction in which the seller engages a few potential brokers and provides limited information about the portfolio being sold. Uncertainty about the portfolio contents reduces bids, effectively increasing the transaction cost paid by the seller. How might a trusted intermediary reduce transaction costs? The authors propose a mechanism through which each party provides relevant private information to an intermediary who ultimately reveals only the portfolio contents and price paid, and only to the seller and winning broker. The insight for management: There may be a substantial potential benefit to sellers of such an intermediary; a seller can reduce expected transaction costs by more than 10% through this approach. Consumer Valuation of Modularly Upgradeable Products (p. 1761) Sezer Ülkü, Claudiu V. Dimofte, Glen M. Schmidt Products such as PCs, cameras, and cell phones can be released more quickly, with more future feature flexibility, and can achieve a longer product life through a modular design. Although product modularity is often advocated as a valuable design strategy in operations, little is known about how consumers respond to modular products. The authors describe consumer response to modularly upgradeable products in settings featuring technological change. They consider both the initial product design choice and the subsequent consumer upgrade decision to replace a module or replace the entire product. The authors find that consumers tend to discount the cost savings associated with modular upgrades excessively when the time between the initial purchase and the upgrade is short and tend to value it excessively over longer intervals. This finding suggests that modular upgradability as a product feature has higher profit potential for slowly rather than rapidly improving products. The authors also observe a preference reversal between the initial purchase and the point of upgrade: At the point of initial purchase, people foresee making a full product replacement in the future, yet, when faced with the actual upgrade decision, they are more likely to revert to modular upgrades. The insight for management: Consumers' perspectives on modular products evolve the use of the product, directly affecting the desirability of modular design.
